<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-683-839  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 683 839.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 3 1990 n298 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ISDN: a field of dreams? Deployment of the technology has been adifficult task. (Integrated Services Digital Network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thyfault, Mary E.; Medina, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The deployment of Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN)technology has been a slow and difficult process, with someindustry observers asserting that ISDN will be rapidly obsoletedby telecommunications technologies with greater bandwidth.andP;  ISDNcombines digital data, voice, and signaling on a single copperwire.andP;  Thus far the business community has expressed very littleinterest in ISDN because of the general lack of applications andlack of understanding of how it would fit into the informationsystems environment.andP;  Other factors inhibiting acceptance includethe Consultative Committee on International Telegraph andTelephone's too-broad definition of the ISDN standard, the lack ofcompatibility between ATandamp;T and Northern Telecom ISDN switches, thehigh cost of the technology and incompatibility with some customerpremise equipment.andP;  ISDN users, though, extol the technology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ISDNOutlookImplementationSystem DevelopmentTrendsMarket AnalysisIntegrated Voice/Data.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>